  "prompt": "What is the major difference between Cognitive Computing and Artificial Intelligence?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between Cognitive Computing and Artificial Intelligence:\n\nCognitive Computing:\n1. Focuses on simulating human thought processes\n2. Emphasizes interaction and collaboration with humans\n3. Aims to assist and enhance human decision-making\n4. Adaptable and context-aware\n5. Uses probabilistic reasoning\n6. More interpretable and transparent\n7. Designed to work alongside humans\n\nArtificial Intelligence:\n1. Focuses on creating intelligent machines\n2. Aims to replicate or replace human intelligence\n3. Goal is to develop autonomous systems\n4. More rules-based and deterministic\n5. Uses algorithmic reasoning\n6. Can be less transparent in decision-making\n7. Often designed to operate independently\n\nCommon characteristics:\n- Both involve machine learning\n- Both use advanced computational techniques\n- Both seek to solve complex problems\n- Both utilize large data sets\n- Both leverage advanced algorithms\n\nPrimary distinction: Cognitive Computing is human-centric and collaborative, while AI is more focused on machine autonomy and independent problem-solving.\n\nPractical example:\n- Cognitive Computing: Medical diagnosis support system\n- AI: Self-driving car navigation system\n\nBoth technologies are evolving and complementary, with increasing overlap in their capabilities.",
